{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_6e4dc6b781354bb09986ca67","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Setup\n2\t\n3\t## Requirements\n4\t\n5\t- Make:\n6\t  - macOS: `$ xcode-select --install`\n7\t  - Linux: [https://www.gnu.org](https://www.gnu.org/software/make)\n8\t  - Windows: `$ choco install make` [https://chocolatey.org](https://chocolatey.org/install)\n9\t- Python: `$ asdf install` (https://asdf-vm.com)[https://asdf-vm.com/guide/getting-started.html]\n10\t- Poetry: [https://python-poetry.org](https://python-poetry.org/docs/#installation)\n11\t\n12\tTo confirm these system dependencies are configured correctly:\n13\t\n14\t```text\n15\t$ make bootstrap\n16\t$ make doctor\n17\t```\n18\t\n19\t## Installation\n20\t\n21\tInstall project dependencies into a virtual environment:\n22\t\n23\t```text\n24\t$ make install\n25\t```\n26\t\n27\t# Local Development\n28\t\n29\tTo start the API server and static site:\n30\t\n31\t```text\n32\t$ make run\n33\t```\n34\t\n35\t## Preview image rendering\n36\t\n37\tView all example images: http://localhost:5000/examples\n38\t\n39\tView test images with automatic reload: http://localhost:5000/test\n40\t\n41\tTo view a specific image with automatic reload, simply drop the file extension.\n42\t\n43\t## Add a new meme template\n44\t\n45\t1. Visit http://localhost:5000/<my_new_template_id>\n46\t2. Add a `default.png` (or JPG) background image in `templates/<my_new_template_id>` directory\n47\t3. Update `config.yml` in the `templates/<my_new_template_id>` directory\n48\t4. Refresh http://localhost:5000/images/<my_new_template_id> to see the example\n49\t5. Adjust `config.yml` as necessary to position and style the text\n50\t6. Visit http://localhost:5000/templates to validate all templates\n51\t\n52\t# Continuous Integration\n53\t\n54\t## Manual\n55\t\n56\tRun the tests:\n57\t\n58\t```text\n59\t$ make test\n60\t```\n61\t\n62\tRun static analysis:\n63\t\n64\t```text\n65\t$ make check\n66\t```\n67\t\n68\t## Automatic\n69\t\n70\tKeep all of the above tasks running on change:\n71\t\n72\t```text\n73\t$ make dev\n74\t```\n75\t\n76\t# Deployment\n77\t\n78\t## Heroku\n79\t\n80\tThis service is built to run on Heroku. Route traffic through a CDN to cache generated images.\n81\t\n82\t## Containerization\n83\t\n84\tYou can also build this service as a container simply by running either of the following commands:\n85\t\n86\t```bash\n87\t# Using Docker:\n88\tdocker build --tag memegen --file Containerfile .\n89\t\n90\t# Using Podman:\n91\tpodman build --tag memegen --file Containerfile .\n92\t```\n93\t\n94\tYou can then run the container by running:\n95\t\n96\t```bash\n97\t# Run the container\n98\tdocker run --publish 5000:5000 --env DOMAIN=\"set.your.domain\" memegen\n99\t\n100\t# Validate functionality\n101\t$ curl http://127.0.0.1:5000/docs/ -sI\n102\tHTTP/1.1 200 OK\n103\tdate: Sun, 24 Oct 2021 19:16:07 GMT\n104\tserver: uvicorn\n105\tlast-modified: Sun, 24 Oct 2021 18:27:30 GMT\n106\tcontent-type: text/html; charset=utf-8\n107\taccess-control-allow-origin: *\n108\t```\n109\t\n110\t<details>\n111\t<summary>Multi-Architecture Builds</summary>\n112\t<br>\n113\t\n114\tIf you want to build the image for multiple CPU architectures, you can either use `buildah` or `docker buildx`. Below are examples for both, and assume you're in the root of the repository:\n115\t\n116\t#### System Requirements\n117\t\n118\tOn Debian/Ubuntu, you'll need to run:\n119\t\n120\t```bash\n121\tsudo apt install --yes podman buildah qemu-user-static\n122\t```\n123\t\n124\tOn any RHEL flavor OS, you'll need to run:\n125\t\n126\t```bash\n127\tsudo yum install --yes podman buildah qemu-user-static\n128\t```\n129\t\n130\tOn Arch or Manjaro Linux, you'll need to run:\n131\t\n132\t```bash\n133\tsudo pacman -Sy podman buildah qemu-arch-extra\n134\t```\n135\t\n136\t#### `docker buildx` Instructions\n137\t\n138\t> This assumes you have [docker buildx](https://docs.docker.com/buildx/working-with-buildx/) already installed!\n139\t\n140\t```bash\n141\tdocker buildx build \\\n142\t    --platform linux/amd64,linux/arm64 \\\n143\t    --tag \"ghcr.io/${GITHUB_USERNAME}/memegen:latest\" \\\n144\t    --push .\n145\t```\n146\t\n147\t#### `buildah` Instructions\n148\t\n149\t```bash\n150\t# Create a multi-architecture manifest\n151\tbuildah manifest create memegen\n152\t\n153\t# Build your amd64 architecture container\n154\tbuildah bud \\\n155\t    --tag \"ghcr.io/${GITHUB_USERNAME}/memegen:latest\" \\\n156\t    --manifest memegen \\\n157\t    --arch amd64 .\n158\t\n159\t# Build your arm64 architecture container\n160\tbuildah bud \\\n161\t    --tag \"ghcr.io/${GITHUB_USERNAME}/memegen:latest\" \\\n162\t    --manifest memegen \\\n163\t    --arch arm64 .\n164\t\n165\t# Enter your GitHub Personal Access Token below\n166\tread -s GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN\n167\t# Log into your GitHub Container Registry\n168\techo \"${GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN}\" | buildah login --username danmanners --password-stdin ghcr.io\n169\t\n170\t# Push the full manifest, with both CPU Architectures\n171\tbuildah manifest push --all memegen \\\n172\t  \"docker://ghcr.io/${GITHUB_USERNAME}/memegen:latest\"\n173\t```\n174\t\n175\t> Please note that building the `--arch arm` build on an `amd64` (Intel/AMD) system can take nearly an hour.\n176\t\n177\t</details>\n178\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8188a1e7-b4c7-41c8-b2b3-c97df30199f1","uuid":"c8744183-5ad5-46d4-8c62-117d415043b5","timestamp":"2026-04-06T23:43:34.671Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/CONTRIBUTING.md","content":"# Setup\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Make:\n  - macOS: `$ xcode-select --install`\n  - Linux: [https://www.gnu.org](https://www.gnu.org/software/make)\n  - Windows: `$ choco install make` [https://chocolatey.org](https://chocolatey.org/install)\n- Python: `$ asdf install` (https://asdf-vm.com)[https://asdf-vm.com/guide/getting-started.html]\n- Poetry: [https://python-poetry.org](https://python-poetry.org/docs/#installation)\n\nTo confirm these system dependencies are configured correctly:\n\n```text\n$ make bootstrap\n$ make doctor\n```\n\n## Installation\n\nInstall project dependencies into a virtual environment:\n\n```text\n$ make install\n```\n\n# Local Development\n\nTo start the API server and static site:\n\n```text\n$ make run\n```\n\n## Preview image rendering\n\nView all example images: http://localhost:5000/examples\n\nView test images with automatic reload: http://localhost:5000/test\n\nTo view a specific image with automatic reload, simply drop the file extension.\n\n## Add a new meme template\n\n1. Visit http://localhost:5000/<my_new_template_id>\n2. Add a `default.png` (or JPG) background image in `templates/<my_new_template_id>` directory\n3. Update `config.yml` in the `templates/<my_new_template_id>` directory\n4. Refresh http://localhost:5000/images/<my_new_template_id> to see the example\n5. Adjust `config.yml` as necessary to position and style the text\n6. Visit http://localhost:5000/templates to validate all templates\n\n# Continuous Integration\n\n## Manual\n\nRun the tests:\n\n```text\n$ make test\n```\n\nRun static analysis:\n\n```text\n$ make check\n```\n\n## Automatic\n\nKeep all of the above tasks running on change:\n\n```text\n$ make dev\n```\n\n# Deployment\n\n## Heroku\n\nThis service is built to run on Heroku. Route traffic through a CDN to cache generated images.\n\n## Containerization\n\nYou can also build this service as a container simply by running either of the following commands:\n\n```bash\n# Using Docker:\ndocker build --tag memegen --file Containerfile .\n\n# Using Podman:\npodman build --tag memegen --file Containerfile .\n```\n\nYou can then run the container by running:\n\n```bash\n# Run the container\ndocker run --publish 5000:5000 --env DOMAIN=\"set.your.domain\" memegen\n\n# Validate functionality\n$ curl http://127.0.0.1:5000/docs/ -sI\nHTTP/1.1 200 OK\ndate: Sun, 24 Oct 2021 19:16:07 GMT\nserver: uvicorn\nlast-modified: Sun, 24 Oct 2021 18:27:30 GMT\ncontent-type: text/html; charset=utf-8\naccess-control-allow-origin: *\n```\n\n<details>\n<summary>Multi-Architecture Builds</summary>\n<br>\n\nIf you want to build the image for multiple CPU architectures, you can either use `buildah` or `docker buildx`. Below are examples for both, and assume you're in the root of the repository:\n\n#### System Requirements\n\nOn Debian/Ubuntu, you'll need to run:\n\n```bash\nsudo apt install --yes podman buildah qemu-user-static\n```\n\nOn any RHEL flavor OS, you'll need to run:\n\n```bash\nsudo yum install --yes podman buildah qemu-user-static\n```\n\nOn Arch or Manjaro Linux, you'll need to run:\n\n```bash\nsudo pacman -Sy podman buildah qemu-arch-extra\n```\n\n#### `docker buildx` Instructions\n\n> This assumes you have [docker buildx](https://docs.docker.com/buildx/working-with-buildx/) already installed!\n\n```bash\ndocker buildx build \\\n    --platform linux/amd64,linux/arm64 \\\n    --tag \"ghcr.io/${GITHUB_USERNAME}/memegen:latest\" \\\n    --push .\n```\n\n#### `buildah` Instructions\n\n```bash\n# Create a multi-architecture manifest\nbuildah manifest create memegen\n\n# Build your amd64 architecture container\nbuildah bud \\\n    --tag \"ghcr.io/${GITHUB_USERNAME}/memegen:latest\" \\\n    --manifest memegen \\\n    --arch amd64 .\n\n# Build your arm64 architecture container\nbuildah bud \\\n    --tag \"ghcr.io/${GITHUB_USERNAME}/memegen:latest\" \\\n    --manifest memegen \\\n    --arch arm64 .\n\n# Enter your GitHub Personal Access Token below\nread -s GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN\n# Log into your GitHub Container Registry\necho \"${GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN}\" | buildah login --username danmanners --password-stdin ghcr.io\n\n# Push the full manifest, with both CPU Architectures\nbuildah manifest push --all memegen \\\n  \"docker://ghcr.io/${GITHUB_USERNAME}/memegen:latest\"\n```\n\n> Please note that building the `--arch arm` build on an `amd64` (Intel/AMD) system can take nearly an hour.\n\n</details>\n","numLines":178,"startLine":1,"totalLines":178}}}
